# Domain Modeling Principles

Use these rules when working on domain entities, domain services, domain validation, or application logic that depends on the internal session/set model.

## Core Rule

Model business meaning first. Do not model the domain around API request shape, voice-API output, or convenience shortcuts.

## Domain Priorities

The domain should prioritize:

- session meaning (start, end, duration, state)
- set and set-group meaning (exercise, weight, reps, notes, order, grouping)
- data consistency (no incomplete or conflicting set persisted without confirmation)
- state semantics (pending, confirmed, persisted)
- explicit invariants (e.g. set belongs to session, group contains sets)

## Preferred Characteristics

Domain code should be:

- explicit
- readable
- deterministic
- easy to test
- isolated from infrastructure
- isolated from voice-API or HTTP transport details

## The Domain Should Own

The domain layer should own:

- session and set invariants
- business validation (e.g. set number, group consistency, session bounds)
- allowed state transitions (e.g. pending → confirmed → persisted)
- relationships among session, set, and set group

## The Domain Should Not Own

The domain layer should not own:

- HTTP concerns
- voice-to-text or parsing logic
- OAuth or token handling
- logging infrastructure
- database framework details

## Modeling Guidelines

Prefer:

- cohesive entities (Session, Set, SetGroup, Exercise, User)
- explicit value objects when useful (e.g. Weight, Reps)
- narrow domain services with clear intent
- explicit naming over generic helpers
- domain rules that can be tested without the framework

Avoid:

- anemic models with logic scattered everywhere
- implicit derived behavior hidden in unrelated utilities
- broad god objects
- generic wrappers that obscure meaning
- mixed domain and integration responsibilities

## Business Semantics Matter

States and relationships must reflect real business meaning.

Do not:

- persist unconfirmed or incomplete sets when the business rule requires confirmation
- blur “parsed” with “confirmed”
- blur “confirmed” with “persisted”
- blur “active session” with “completed session”

## Final Rule

If the model becomes easier for the transport or voice layer but less faithful to the business workflow, the modeling direction is wrong.
